title: For Sale:  Kel Tec RFB 308 Bull-Pup Tactical Rifle
postcontent:
This is the VERY hard to find Tan ceracote version of this rifle.  It will not last long.  I will not entertain trades or low-ball offers.  The first person with the money gets it, I will not take payments.  Here are the details on this rifle. 
BRAND NEW IN BOX!!!!
Davidson's Lifetime replacement warranty. 3% cc fee. RFB stands for Rifle, Forward-ejecting Bullpup. Why forward-ejecting? Because it allows the RFB to be the first truly ambidextrous 7.62 NATO Bullpup ever developed. The patented, dual-extractor system maintains control of the case from the moment it leaves the magazine and upon firing, pulls the fired case from the chamber and lifts them to push them into an ejection chute above the barrel, where they exit. The Bullpup configuration and tilting-block mechanism allow the 18" model to be only 26.1" long, or as much as 14" shorter in overall length than its competitors with equal barrel lengths. Furthermore, the stock and mechanism cross-section is similar to a conventional rifle, in stark contrast to existing Bullpup rifles. The RFB is also the safest Bullpup ever developed because the breech is separated from the shooters face by two layers of 1.6 mm steel. In the highly unlikely event of a case rupture, gas expansion is directed downwards through the magazine well to protect the shooters head and face. TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS Calibers: Target Carbine Weight unloaded (no magazine): 11.3 lbs 8.1 lbs Length: 40" 26" Barrel length: 32" 18" Magazine: 10 or 20 FAL Practical range: 1200m 600m The RFB is a short-stroke gas piston operated semi-automatic rifle in 7.62 mm NATO caliber. It accepts standard metric FAL type magazines which work "drop free" and do not need to be tilted in. One 20 round magazine is included*. Barrels on current models are 18" long, with a chrome lined bore and chamber. The muzzle is threaded 5/8x24 TPI and comes equipped with our A2-style Flash Hider*. Longer barrel lengths of 24", 26" and 32" will be available in the future. All controls are fully ambidextrous; the reciprocating operating handle can be switched to either side. The trigger mechanism is second to no other Bullpup ever built and better than nearly all commercial semi-auto rifles. The safety disconnects the trigger and blocks the hammer action. A Mil-Spec Picatinny rail is attached rigidly to the barrel. No open sights are provided, allowing the user to select from the very best new optics and sight systems available. The RFB comes with a two point sling that can be easily configured to suit the user's preference. Available accessories include a free-floating, four-sided Picatinny forend, bipod mounts, a removable bayonet lug for use with NATO style bayonets including our own Folding Bayonet, and many more.

title: For Sale:  Kriss Super V with extras - LOW PRICE
postcontent:
OK, hate to put this thing up for sale, but holiday cash is at an all time low and I need to sell off a few firearms.  Up for sale is my Kriss Super V.  This gun shoots .45ACP.  Included in with the firearm is the forward grip with the spring loaded bi-pod.  Also included is a red-dot sighting system, already sighted for 50 yards.  This includes 1 standard magazine and an extended brand new/never used 30 round magazine.  The gun has only had 300 rounds fired through it.  I challenge you to find one anywhere near this price in this condition.

If you have never had the pleasure of firing a Kriss Super V, it has the pivoting bolt, which slides down rather than back, producing nearly zero recoil and muzzle raise.  The Kriss (which fires a .45ACP round) has 60% less recoil and 90% less muzzle raise than a H&K MP5 (which fires a the smaller 9mm round).  The charging handle also does not slide back with the bolt.  Since it remains stationary, it also adds to the smoothness of the rifle.  You can just put it on your target, unload the magazine and the gun will stay right in place.

I can provide my original receipt with this purchase to prove ownership.  I really need a quick sale and will be posting this at a little over $500 less than what I have invested in the gun.  

Please call me with any questions or would like to see the rifle.  Willing to travel within reason to meet you FTF.

Remington 870 Wingmaster Magnum .12 gauge pump shotgun for sell or trade. Don't need to get rid of it, but since I already have a tactical build shotgun I just thought I would see what is out there. I am interested in selling or trading and will entertain reasonable offers.

CASH PRICE: $325 without the S2AR grip adapter, $400 with the S2AR grip adapter, or a trade. I'll throw in a box or two of 00 buckshot as well; willing to add cash for right deal or take lesser trade with cash difference.

The S2AR grip adapter is not shown, but you can see what it looks like here:

http://www.elitetacticaladvantage.com/

This has a magnum receiver, will shoot 3" shells, and has the all metal trigger plate assembly, not the newer polymer ones. It has wood stock/forend and they are nice condition, has chrome breech bolt assembly. The barrel is a new Mossberg manufactured 18.5" Cylinder bore, 2 3/4" & 3" chambered (I gave the original barrel away to a friend who hunts w/a Wingmaster), and the magazine extension is a 2 round Scattergun Technologies extension. The shotgun also has a new sling, will come with the original magazine tube spring and magazine spring retainer as well as an extra magazine cap (that came with the sling) and original follower (has the new high vis one that came with the Scattergun Technologies mag extension in it now). 

The receiver was refinished with Aluma-Hyde II, Dark Parkerizing Gray a while back. Overall the shotgun is in good-very good shape, but it's a shooter so it's not mint. It's a solid home defense shotgun and would make a great tactical shotgun with new furniture. To get you started in that direction, I have a brand new Elite Tactical Advantages S2AR grip adapter which allows you to attach any standard AR grip, buffer tube and stock, putting the stock in direct line w/the barrel so you can have the same ergonomics as an AR platform and make use of recoil reducing stocks/buffer systems.

In the 1990, after the excessive trials, South Korean army adopted the first domestically designed 9mm pistol, the K5. Developed and manufactured in Korea by the Daewoo Precision Industries branch of the Daewoo Corporation, the K5 pistol is now standard sidearm of the armed forces of South Korea.  The basic 9mm K5 is sold as Daewoo DP-51, its compact variant is sold as DP-51c, and the variant in the .40SW is sold as DH-40. These pistols are well made and shoot well.

Daewoo K5 / DP51 pistol is short recoil operated, locked breech weapon. It uses a conventional Browning-type locking system, with two lugs on the barrel engaging cuts inside the slide. Locking and unlocking is controlled by the cam-shaped lug at the bottom of the barrel. Frame of the pistol is made from aluminum alloy; all other parts are made from steel. Trigger is of “triple action” type. This means that other than traditional double or single action fire modes it has “fast action” mode, apparently borrowed from FN’s GP “Fast Action” pistol. In this mode hammer is cocked by the cycle of the slide, then it is pushed forward by the pressure on the hammer head. In this position, the main spring remains cocked, so only light pressure on the trigger is necessary to recock the hammer and fire the gun in the “double action manner”. Or, alternatively, hammer can be recocked manually to be fired in single action for maximum first-shot accuracy. Sights are fixed, with the rear sight dovetailed to the slide. Magazines are of double stack type; proprietary magazines hold 13 rounds, but DP-51 also can use Smith-Wesson 5906 magazines, which will slightly protrude from the bottom of the grip.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Victory 38 revolver
postcontent:
This is a Smith & Wesson Victory Model 38 S&W cal revolver

Victories were produced for the "Lend Lease" program during WWII and shipped to Australia, New Zealand, Britain and other allied countries as well as to defense contractors in the US for security personnel.

This particular revolver was produced in late 1943 or early 1944 and has been refinished in nickel with white grips and modified to fire the S&W 38 special ctg. It will now fire both the 38 S&W and the 38 S&W special cartridge.

Here are the markings;

Bottom of barrel; V2679xx
Left side of barrel; Smith & Wesson
Right side of bbl; 38 S&W CTG then a different stamp; SPECIAL
Above the trigger guard on right side; Made in USA
Right side plate; S&W logo stamp
Bottom of butt; V2679xx
Rear of cylinder; V2679xx
Crane; N 21359 21359
There are no other marks, proof marks or US Property marks.
These numbers mean that all the parts are original to this gun.

The nickel is OK, some minor scratches but on the right side it looks like road rash. The cylinder has some moderate scratches and the end of the barrel has some chips in the nickel. The lanyard ring hole on the butt is apparant where it was filled before refinish.

The timing seems good, the lock up is tight and the trigger is wonderful(it is a S&W after all).

I have fired 38 special rounds in this revolver and it is an easy to shoot quality S&W revolver and would make a great inexpensive home defense weapon for the person who wants something less complicated than a semi-auto. And it has some historical significance.

 This is a great example of one of the more sought after SKS rifles. When I first got into military type rifles I was more into SKS and AK type variants . I did my homework and bought this weapon 25 years ago. I selected this rifle out of a crate full , unwrapped it and wiped off the cosmoline grease it was coated in. I have shot it less than 500 rounds. ( I purchased 500 rounds with it and still have a few boxes )
******/26\ has factory 26 proof mark *****
**** this is a Sino-Soviet Rifle built in the first run after Russian Arsenal Tula moved its tooling to a Norinco factory... Early Chinese manufactured SKS's were stamped with a 26 inside a Triangle and  Chinese characters which translated to Type 56, the model designation of the Chinese SKS. Note the orientation of these characters / proof marks. These were built in the only Russian supervised arsenal located at the Jianshe armory. Note the serial number, starting with Western type letter followed by 4 numbers.

The Museum of the Confederacy Tribute Revolver combines the classic design of the fabled LeMat revolver with striking 24-karat gold and nickel artwork honoring the legacy of the Confederate soldiers and their leaders who valiantly fought for the cause of the Confederacy.

The LeMat's unique nine-shot cylinder holds the portraits of three of the Confederacy's favorite sons. Right side features revered Confederate General Robert E. Lee, and the left side features the gallant Cavalry Major General J.E.B. Stuart. 

Both are surrounded by flowing scrollwork and crossed rifles of the Confederate Infantry. Jefferson Davis, President of the Confederate States of America, is featured on top of the cylinder.

The frame of the Tribute is adorned on both sides with a Confederate flag displayed within a field of scrollwork. The "CS", or Confederate States, belt buckle is featured on the breech of the barrel. The official seal of the Museum of the Confederacy is also featured on the smoothbore shotgun barrel, surrounded by matching scrollwork.

Along the right side of the barrel, the issue is identified as "The Museum of the Confederacy Tribute" in a classic banner tipped in matching scrollwork. Each Tribute's individual edition number is featured on top of the barrel near the sight.

One of the most commonly used sidearms of the Union Army during the Civil War the 1860 Colt was a workhorse. This replica's not too bad either. It's a six shot cap and ball revolver. It's lots of fun, but I just don't use it that much. Besides the revolver, I'm including a powder horn, a powder measure, .44 caliber balls, #11 percussion caps, the manual, and a cleaning kit (patches, bore butter, lube and bore cleaner.)

I have shot it pretty sparingly so some of the powder, caps and balls are used, but the vast majority of them are there. I just didn't feel like counting. 

I'm pretty firm on the price since it comes with all the accessories.
